<http://example.org/pt#stmt_146> prov:value "This is partly because This southern extension into the outer suburbs was not done by taking over an existing surface line as was generally the case with routes such as the Central, Jubilee and Piccadilly lines.",
        "Urban myths Owing to Road historically circular nature, the line has generated many urban myths over the years, including a dead man travelling around undiscovered, a school or office using the service to save infrastructure costs and, as an April fool in the Independent, a new particle accelerator to coexist alongside passenger services.[46][71][72]" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_147> prov:value "Apart from the core central underground tunnels, part of the section between Hendon and Colindale is also underground." .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_148> prov:value "As bicycles are not allowed in tunnel sections (even if no station is in that section) as bicycles would hinder evacuation, bicycles are limited to High Barnet – East Finchley, the Mill Hill East branch, Edgware – Colindale and Hendon Central – Golders Green.[83] There are also time-based restrictions for the sections where bicycles are allowed.[83] The tunnel from Morden to East Finchley via Bank, 17 miles 528 yards (27.841 km),[1] was for a time the longest rail tunnel in the world." .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_149> prov:value "As bicycles are not allowed in tunnel sections (even if no station is in that section) as bicycles would hinder evacuation, bicycles are limited to High Barnet – East Finchley, the Mill Hill East branch, Edgware – Colindale and Hendon Central – Golders Green.[83] There are also time-based restrictions for the sections where bicycles are allowed.[83] The tunnel from Morden to East Finchley via Bank, 17 miles 528 yards (27.841 km),[1] was for a time the longest rail tunnel in the world." .

