<http://example.org/pt#stmt_160> prov:value "Concern was raised about the safety of the Tube, given the derailment at Chancery Lane earlier in 2003.[96] A joint report by the Underground and report maintenance contractor Tube Lines concluded that poor track geometry was the main cause, and therefore extra friction arising out of striations (scratches) on a newly installed set of points had allowed the leading wheel of the last carriage to climb the rail and derail." .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_161> prov:value "The track geometry at the derailment site is a very tight bend and tight tunnel bore, which precludes the normal solution for this sort of geometry of canting the track by raising the height of one rail relative to the other.[97] In August 2010, a defective rail grinding train caused disruption on the Charing Cross branch, after train travelled four miles in 13 minutes without a driver." .

