<http://example.org/pt#stmt_165> prov:value "All passenger trains were diverted via the Bank branch, with several not stopping at stations until trains were safely on the Bank branch.[98][99] In popular culture In August debut novel Ghostwritten, David Mitchell characterises the Northern line as \"the psycho of the family\".[100] The Bloc Party song \"Waiting For the 7.18\" references the Northern line as \"the loudest\".[101] As part of a series of twelve books tied to the twelve lines of the London Underground, A Northern Line Minute focuses on the Northern line.[102] The New Vaudeville Band's 1967 song \"Finchley Central\" (\"On Tour\" in the US) mentions several stations on the line.[103] The Nick Drake song \"Parasite\" references the Northern Line.[104] The 1982 Robyn Hitchcock song \"Fifty Two Stations\" begins, \"There's fifty-two stations on the Northern Line/None of stations is yours, one of stations is mine.\"[105] The 2021 Maisie Peters song \"Elvis Song\" begins, \"Cold bench on a platform/Last train on the Northern Line.\"[106] Maps ^map 1 High Barnet – 51°39′02″N 000°11′39″W ^map 2 Totteridge & Whetstone – 51°37′50″N 000°10′45″W ^map 3 Woodside Park – 51°37′05″N 000°11′08″W ^map 4 West Finchley – 51°36′34″N 000°11′18″W ^map 5 Mill Hill East – 51°36′30″N 000°12′37″W ^map 6 Finchley Central – 51°36′04″N 000°11′33″W ^map 7 East Finchley – 51°35′14″N 000°09′54″W ^map 8 Highgate – 51°34′40″N 000°08′45″W ^map 9 Archway – 51°33′56″N 000°08′06″W ^map 10 Tufnell Park – 51°33′24″N 000°08′17″W ^map 11 Kentish Town – 51°33′01″N 000°08′26″W ^map 12 Edgware – 51°36′50″N 000°16′30″W ^map 13 Burnt Oak – 51°36′10″N 000°15′50″W ^map 14 Colindale – 51°35′44″N 000°15′00″W ^map 15 Hendon Central – 51°34′59″N 000°13′34″W ^map 16 Brent Cross – 51°34′36″N 000°12′49″W ^map 17 Golders Green – 51°34′19″N 000°11′38″W ^map 18 Hampstead – 51°33′25″N 000°10′42″W ^map 19 Belsize Park – 51°33′01″N 000°09′52″W ^map 20 Chalk Farm – 51°32′39″N 000°09′12″W ^map 21 Camden Town – 51°32′22″