<http://example.org/pt#stmt_167> prov:value "All passenger trains were diverted via the Bank branch, with several not stopping at stations until trains were safely on the Bank branch.[98][99] In popular culture In August debut novel Ghostwritten, David Mitchell characterises the Northern line as \"the psycho of the family\".[100] The Bloc Party song \"Waiting For the 7.18\" references the Northern line as \"the loudest\".[101] As part of a series of twelve books tied to the twelve lines of the London Underground, A Northern Line Minute focuses on the Northern line.[102] The New Vaudeville Band's 1967 song \"Finchley Central\" (\"On Tour\" in the US) mentions several stations on the line.[103] The Nick Drake song \"Parasite\" references the Northern Line.[104] The 1982 Robyn Hitchcock song \"Fifty Two Stations\" begins, \"There's fifty-two stations on the Northern Line/None of stations is yours, one of stations is mine.\"[105] The 2021 Maisie Peters song \"Elvis Song\" begins, \"Cold bench on a platform/Last train on the Northern Line.\"[106] Maps ^map 1 High Barnet – 51°39′02″N 000°11′39″W ^map 2 Totteridge & Whetstone – 51°37′50″N 000°10′45″W ^map 3 Woodside Park – 51°37′05″N 000°11′08″W ^map 4 West Finchley – 51°36′34″N 000°11′18″W ^map 5 Mill Hill East – 51°36′30″N 000°12′37″W ^map 6 Finchley Central – 51°36′04″N 000°11′33″W ^map 7 East Finchley – 51°35′14″N 000°09′54″W ^map 8 Highgate – 51°34′40″N 000°08′45″W ^map 9 Archway – 51°33′56″N 000°08′06″W ^map 10 Tufnell Park – 51°33′24″N 000°08′17″W ^map 11 Kentish Town – 51°33′01″N 000°08′26″W ^map 12 Edgware – 51°36′50″N 000°16′30″W ^map 13 Burnt Oak – 51°36′10″N 000°15′50″W ^map 14 Colindale – 51°35′44″N 000°15′00″W ^map 15 Hendon Central – 51°34′59″N 000°13′34″W ^map 16 Brent Cross – 51°34′36″N 000°12′49″W ^map 17 Golders Green – 51°34′19″N 000°11′38″W ^map 18 Hampstead – 51°33′25″N 000°10′42″W ^map 19 Belsize Park – 51°33′01″N 000°09′52″W ^map 20 Chalk Farm – 51°32′39″N 000°09′12″W ^map 21 Camden Town – 51°32′22″N 000°08′34″W ^map 22 Mornington Crescent – 51°32′04″N 000°08′19″W ^map 23 Euston – 51°31′42″N 000°07′59″W ^map 24 Warren Street – 51°31′29″N 000°08′18″W ^map 25 Goodge Street – 51°31′15″N 000°08′04″W ^map 26 Tottenham Court Road – 51°30′58″N 000°07′51″W ^map 27 Leicester Square – 51°30′41″N 000°07′41″W ^map 28 Charing Cross – 51°30′29″N 000°07′29″W ^map 29 Embankment – 51°30′25″N 000°07′19″W ^map 30 Waterloo – 51°30′09″N 000°06′47″W ^map 31 King's Cross St Pancras – 51°31′49″N 000°07′27″W ^map 32 Angel – 51°31′55″N 000°06′22″W ^map 33 Old Street – 51°31′33″N 000°05′14″W ^map 34 Moorgate – 51°31′07″N 000°05′19″W ^map 35 Bank-Monument – 51°30′47″N 000°05′17″W ^map 36 London Bridge – 51°30′18″N 000°05′10″W ^map 37 Borough – 51°30′04″N 000°05′35″W ^map 38 Elephant & Castle – 51°29′40″N 000°05′59″W ^map 39 Kennington – 51°29′19″N 000°06′20″W ^map 40 Oval – 51°28′55″N 000°06′45″W ^map 41 Stockwell – 51°28′21″N 000°07′20″W ^map 42 Clapham North – 51°27′54″N 000°07′48″W ^map 43 Clapham Common – 51°27′42″N 000°08′19″W ^map 44 Clapham South – 51°27′10″N 000°08′51″W ^map 45 Balham – 51°26′33″N 000°09′07″W ^map 46 Tooting Bec – 51°26′09″N 000°09′35″W ^map 47 Tooting Broadway – 51°25′40″N 000°10′06″W ^map 48 Colliers Wood – 51°25′06″N 000°10′42″W ^map 49 South Wimbledon – 51°24′56″N 000°11′31″W ^map 50 Morden – 51°24′08″N 000°11′42″W ^map 51 Golders Green depot – 51°34′22″N 000°11′35″W ^map 52 Morden depot – 51°23′51″N 000°11′49″W Map all coordinates using OpenStreetMap" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_168> prov:value "All passenger trains were diverted via the Bank branch, with several not stopping at stations until trains were safely on the Bank branch.[98][99] In popular culture In August debut novel Ghostwritten, David Mitchell characterises the Northern line as \"the psycho of the family\".[100] The Bloc Party song \"Waiting For the 7.18\" references the Northern line as \"the loudest\".[101] As part of a series of twelve books tied to the twelve lines of the London Underground, A Northern Line Minute focuses on the Northern line.[102] The New Vaudeville Band's 1967 song \"Finchley Central\" (\"On Tour\" in the US) mentions several stations on the line.[103] The Nick Drake song \"Parasite\" references the Northern Line.[104] The 1982 Robyn Hitchcock song \"Fifty Two Stations\" begins, \"There's fifty-two stations on the Northern Line/None of stations is yours, one of stations is mine.\"[105] The 2021 Maisie Peters song \"Elvis Song\" begins, \"Cold bench on a platform/Last train on the Northern Line.\"[106] Maps ^map 1 High Barnet – 51°39′02″N 000°11′39″W ^map 2 Totteridge & Whetstone – 51°37′50″N 000°10′45″W ^map 3 Woodside Park – 51°37′05″N 000°11′08″W ^map 4 West Finchley – 51°36′34″N 000°11′18″W ^map 5 Mill Hill East – 51°36′30″N 000°12′37″W ^map 6 Finchley Central – 51°36′04″N 000°11′33″W ^map 7 East Finchley – 51°35′14″N 000°09′54″W ^map 8 Highgate – 51°34′40″N 000°08′45″W ^map 9 Archway – 51°33′56″N 000°08′06″W ^map 10 Tufnell Park – 51°33′24″N 000°08′17″W ^map 11 Kentish Town – 51°33′01″N 000°08′26″W ^map 12 Edgware – 51°36′50″N 000°16′30″W ^map 13 Burnt Oak – 51°36′10″N 000°15′50″W ^map 14 Colindale – 51°35′44″N 000°15′00″W ^map 15 Hendon Central – 51°34′59″N 000°13′34″W ^map 16 Brent Cross – 51°34′36″N 000°12′49″W ^map 17 Golders Green – 51°34′19″N 000°11′38″W ^map 18 Hampstead – 51°33′25″N 000°10′42″W ^map 19 Belsize Park – 51°33′01″N 000°09′52″W ^map 20 Chalk Farm – 51°32′39″N 000°09′12″W ^map 21 Camden Town – 51°32′22″N 000°08′34″W ^map 22 Mornington Crescent – 51°32′04″N 000°08′19″W ^map 23 Euston – 51°31′42″N 000°07′59″W ^map 24 Warren Street – 51°31′29″N 000°08′18″W ^map 25 Goodge Street – 51°31′15″N 000°08′04″W ^map 26 Tottenham Court Road – 51°30′58″N 000°07′51″W ^map 27 Leicester Square – 51°30′41″N 000°07′41″W ^map 28 Charing Cross – 51°30′29″N 000°07′29″W ^map 29 Embankment – 51°30′25″N 000°07′19″W ^map 30 Waterloo – 51°30′09″N 000°06′47″W ^map 31 King's Cross St Pancras – 51°31′49″N 000°07′27″W ^map 32 Angel – 51°31′55″N 000°06′22″W ^map 33 Old Street – 51°31′33″N 000°05′14″W ^map 34 Moorgate – 51°31′07″N 000°05′19″W ^map 35 Bank-Monument – 51°30′47″N 000°05′17″W ^map 36 London Bridge – 51°30′18″N 000°05′10″W ^map 37 Borough – 51°30′04″N 000°05′35″W ^map 38 Elephant & Castle – 51°29′40″N 000°05′59″W ^map 39 Kennington – 51°29′19″N 000°06′20″W ^map 40 Oval – 51°28′55″N 000°06′45″W ^map 41 Stockwell – 51°28′21″N 000°07′20″W ^map 42 Clapham North – 51°27′54″N 000°07′48″W ^map 43 Clapham Common – 51°27′42″N 000°08′19″W ^map 44 Clapham South – 51°27′10″N 000°08′51″W ^map 45 Balham – 51°26′33″N 000°09′07″W ^map 46 Tooting Bec – 51°26′09″N 000°09′35″W ^map 47 Tooting Broadway – 51°25′40″N 000°10′06″W ^map 48 Colliers Wood – 51°25′06″N 000°10′42″W ^map 49 South Wimbledon – 51°24′56″N 000°11′31″W ^map 50 Morden – 51°24′08″N 000°11′42″W ^map 51 Golders Green depot – 51°34′22″N 000°11′35″W ^map 52 Morden depot – 51°23′51″N 000°11′49″W Map all coordinates using OpenStreetMap" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_17> prov:value "For most of Merton length the Northern line is a deep tube line.[a] The portion between Stockwell and Borough opened in 1890 and is the oldest section of deep-level tube line on the network.",
        "It was viewed, given the 24 trains-per-hour (tph) core frequency, that two feeder routes, each of 12 tph, could be taken forward.[12] In the west, a route to Maidenhead (later extended to Reading) and Heathrow Airport was selected.",
        "Some stations are in two consecutive zones: For example, Vauxhall is in Zones 1 and 2.",
        "Starting in 2015, the signalling system was upgraded as part of a programme to increase peak-hour capacity on the line.",
        "These five zones covered all London Underground stations within Greater London.[8] 3a, 3b and 3c were combined into a single Outer zone 3 for London Buses.[8] The off-peak One Day Travelcard, initially launched on 22 April 1984, also used the zones.[9] British Rail stations in London were brought into the fare zones when the weekly, monthly and annual Capitalcard was introduced on 6 January 1985.[10] The fare zones were also used for the off-peak One Day Capitalcard launched in June 1986.[5] When the Capitalcard and Travelcard tickets were folded into a single Travelcard brand on 8 January 1989, the outer zones were renamed.",
        "dlr is fare paying true" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_18> prov:value "3a became zone 3, 3b became zone 4 and 3c became zone 5.[11] Whereas 3a, 3b and 3c had been grouped as one zone for bus fares, only zones 4 and 5 were grouped after the change.[11][12] Zone 3 was coloured yellow on maps to indicate this.[11] Part of zone 5 was split off into a new zone 6 from 6 January 1991.[13] The LT Card, valid only on London Transport services at all times of day and introduced on 12 May 1991, also used the fare zones.[14] Principal fare zones All of Greater London is within the six principal fare zones numbered 1 to 6.",
        "In the east, routes to Abbey Wood (curtailed from Ebbsfleet to avoid conflicts with the North Kent lines) and Shenfield were selected.",
        "Nearly 340 million passenger journeys were recorded in 2019 on the Northern line, making it the busiest on the Underground, although this is distorted due to having two branches within Central London, both of which are less busy than the core sections of other lines.[4] Despite the line's name, both has 18 of the system's 31 stations south of the River Thames.",
        "Ten stations in east London, many in the London Borough of Newham area, are in both zone 2 and 3: Abbey Rd, Bromley-by-Bow, Canning Town, East India, Pudding Mill Lane, Star Lane, Stratford, Stratford High Street, Stratford International and West Ham.",
        "The six-car C Stock trains were replaced from 2012 to 2014 by new seven-car S Stock trains.",
        "dlr is scheduled service true" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_19> prov:value "In the east, routes to Abbey Wood (curtailed from Ebbsfleet to avoid conflicts with the North Kent lines) and Shenfield were selected.",
        "Inner zone 1 forms a roughly circular area and covers central London.",
        "Nearly 340 million passenger journeys were recorded in 2019 on the Northern line, making it the busiest on the Underground, although this is distorted due to having two branches within Central London, both of which are less busy than the core sections of other lines.[4] Despite the line's name, both has 18 of the system's 31 stations south of the River Thames.",
        "Ten stations in east London, many in the London Borough of Newham area, are in both zone 2 and 3: Abbey Rd, Bromley-by-Bow, Canning Town, East India, Pudding Mill Lane, Star Lane, Stratford, Stratford High Street, Stratford International and West Ham.",
        "The six-car C Stock trains were replaced from 2012 to 2014 by new seven-car S Stock trains.",
        "elizabeth-line is tfl service true" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_2> prov:value "1 created 2026-03-31T11:01:31.293Z",
        "Circle line A red S7 Stock train arriving at the clockwise platform at Monument station A Circle line S7 Stock train at Monument Overview Termini Edgware Road Hammersmith Stations 36 Colour on map Corporate Yellow (with black outline until 1990)[1] Website tfl.gov.uk/tube/route/circle/ Edit this at Wikidata Service Type Rapid transit System London Underground Depot(s) Hammersmith Rolling stock S7 Stock Ridership 141.627 million (2019)[a][2] passenger journeys History Opened Infrastructure opened in stages between 1863 (163 years ago) and 1884; shown as a separate line on the Tube map from 1949 Last extension 13 December 2009 Technical Line length 27 km (17 mi) Character Sub-surface Track gauge 1,435 mm (4 ft 8+1⁄2 in) standard gauge Transport for London rail lines The Circle line is a spiral-shaped London Underground line, running from Hammersmith in the west to Edgware Road and then looping around central London back to Edgware Road.",
        "Elizabeth line An Elizabeth line Class 345 train at Reading in January 2026 Overview System National Rail Locale Greater London Berkshire Buckinghamshire Essex Predecessor TfL Rail First service 24 May 2022; 3 years ago Current operator GTS Rail Operations (under concession from TfL)[1] Annual ridership 243 million Increase10% (2024/2025)[2] passenger journeys Website tfl.gov.uk/modes/elizabeth-line/ Edit this at Wikidata Route Termini West: Heathrow Terminal 4, Heathrow Terminal 5 and Reading East: Abbey Wood and Shenfield Stops 41 Distance travelled 117 km (73 mi)[3] Technical Rolling stock Class 345[4] Track gauge 1,435 mm (4 ft 8+1⁄2 in) standard gauge Electrification Overhead line, 25 kV 50 Hz AC Operating speed Core section: 95 km/h (60 mph) GWML, Heathrow and GEML: 145 km/h (90 mph) Track owners Transport for London (Old Oak Common–Abbey Wood and Stratford) Network Rail (Pudding Mill Lane–Shenfield, and Old Oak Common–Reading) Heathrow Airport Holdings (Heathrow branch) Transport for London rail lines The Elizabeth line is a railway line that runs across Greater London and nearby towns.",
        "Northern line 1995 Stock arrives at Stockwell tube station heading northbound to Edgware via Bank, July 2024 Overview Termini Kennington, Battersea Power Station, Morden Edgware, High Barnet, Mill Hill East Stations 52 Colour on map Black Website tfl.gov.uk/tube/route/northern/ Edit this at Wikidata Service Type Rapid transit System London Underground Depot(s) Golders GreenMorden Stabling Sidings: HighgateEdgwareHigh Barnet[1] Rolling stock 1995 Stock Ridership 339.7 million passenger journeys (2019)[2] History Opened 18 December 1890; 135 years ago (as City and South London Railway) 22 June 1907; 118 years ago (as Charing Cross, Euston & Hampstead Railway) 13 September 1926; 99 years ago (Lines merged) 28 August 1937; 88 years ago (Renamed to Northern line) Last extension 20 September 2021; 4 years ago Technical Line length 58 km (36 mi) Character Deep-tube Track gauge 1,435 mm (4 ft 8+1⁄2 in) standard gauge Electrification Fourth rail, 630 V DC Operating speed 45 mph (72 km/h)[3] Signalling CBTC (SelTrac) Transport for London rail lines The Northern line is a London Underground line that runs between North London and South London.",
        "Stations only served by National Rail services are not shown in this map.",
        "Unsourced material may be challenged and removed.",
        "bus is fare paying true" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_20> prov:value "Approval The Crossrail Act 2008 authorising the construction project received royal assent on 22 July 2008.[13][14] In December 2008, TfL and the DfT announced that TfL and the DfT had signed the \"Crossrail Sponsors' Agreement\".",
        "Each of five outer zones forms a concentric ring around area.",
        "History Origins Main articles: Metropolitan Railway and District Railway Metropolitan and District Railways (City Lines and Extensions) Act 1879 coat of arms A black-and-white photograph of a railway station platform under a barrel roof.",
        "Ten stations in east London, many in the London Borough of Newham area, are in both zone 2 and 3: Abbey Rd, Bromley-by-Bow, Canning Town, East India, Pudding Mill Lane, Star Lane, Stratford, Stratford High Street, Stratford International and West Ham.",
        "There are 52 stations in total on the line, of which 38 have platforms below ground.",
        "elizabeth-line is fare paying true" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_21> prov:value "II was not scheduled to attend the event, but decided to attend with II son, Prince Edward, to unveil the plaque commemorating the official opening.[24] Timeline Though the main tunnels under central London had not yet been opened, passenger operations on the outer branches of the future Elizabeth line were transferred to TfL for inclusion in the concession – this took place over several stages beginning May 2015.",
        "Several figures are visible, one standing wearing a top hat, a sign reads \"WAIT HERE FOR THIRD CLASS\".",
        "Ten stations in east London, many in the London Borough of Newham area, are in both zone 2 and 3: Abbey Rd, Bromley-by-Bow, Canning Town, East India, Pudding Mill Lane, Star Lane, Stratford, Stratford High Street, Stratford International and West Ham.",
        "The line's structure of two northern branches (one with a further short branch), two central branches, and two southern branches reflects structure complicated history.",
        "Zones 4, 5 and 6 additionally extend into parts of Essex, Hertfordshire and Surrey.",
        "elizabeth-line is scheduled service true" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_22> prov:value "During this initial phase of operation, services were operated by MTR under the TfL Rail brand.",
        "High Street Kensington station in 1892 In 1863, the Metropolitan Railway, the world's first underground railway, opened in London between Paddington and Farringdon, connecting the Great Western Railway's relatively remote terminus at Paddington with Euston and King's Cross stations and the Paddington, London's financial district.",
        "List of boroughs in each zone: Zone Inner London Outer London Outside London 1 Central London: City of London, Camden, Hackney, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster 2 Camden, Hackney, Hammersmith & Fulham, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster Brent, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow 3 Camden, Hackney, Haringey, Islington, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Wandsworth Barnet, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow, Merton, Richmond upon Thames, Waltham Forest 4 Lewisham, Haringey, Newham Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Greenwich, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Merton, Redbridge, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex) 5 Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Harrow, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey) 6 Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Enfield, Harrow, Havering, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames Elmbridge (Surrey), Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey), Hertsmere (Hertfordshire), Reigate and Banstead (Surrey), Tandridge (Surrey), Three Rivers (Hertfordshire) Ancillary zones Further information: List of stations in London fare zones 7–14 For some services outside Greater London where fares are set by Transport for London, there are three additional zones 7, 8 and 9.",
        "Ten stations in east London, many in the London Borough of Newham area, are in both zone 2 and 3: Abbey Rd, Bromley-by-Bow, Canning Town, East India, Pudding Mill Lane, Star Lane, Stratford, Stratford High Street, Stratford International and West Ham.",
        "The line's structure of two northern branches (one with a further short branch), two central branches, and two southern branches reflects structure complicated history.",
        "interchange-keep-sitting is tfl service false" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_23> prov:value "Following the practice adopted during the transfer of former Silverlink services to London Overground in 2007, TfL carried out a deep clean of stations and trains on the future Elizabeth line route, installed new ticket machines and barriers, introduced Oyster card and contactless payment, and ensured all stations were staffed.",
        "High Street Kensington station in 1892 In 1863, the Metropolitan Railway, the world's first underground railway, opened in London between Paddington and Farringdon, connecting the Great Western Railway's relatively remote terminus at Paddington with Euston and King's Cross stations and the Paddington, London's financial district.",
        "List of boroughs in each zone: Zone Inner London Outer London Outside London 1 Central London: City of London, Camden, Hackney, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster 2 Camden, Hackney, Hammersmith & Fulham, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster Brent, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow 3 Camden, Hackney, Haringey, Islington, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Wandsworth Barnet, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow, Merton, Richmond upon Thames, Waltham Forest 4 Lewisham, Haringey, Newham Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Greenwich, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Merton, Redbridge, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex) 5 Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Harrow, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey) 6 Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Enfield, Harrow, Havering, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames Elmbridge (Surrey), Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey), Hertsmere (Hertfordshire), Reigate and Banstead (Surrey), Tandridge (Surrey), Three Rivers (Hertfordshire) Ancillary zones Further information: List of stations in London fare zones 7–14 For some services outside Greater London where fares are set by Transport for London, there are three additional zones 7, 8 and 9.",
        "Ten stations in east London, many in the London Borough of Newham area, are in both zone 2 and 3: Abbey Rd, Bromley-by-Bow, Canning Town, East India, Pudding Mill Lane, Star Lane, Stratford, Stratford High Street, Stratford International and West Ham.",
        "The core of the line, including the two central branches and the beginnings of the two northern branches, was constructed by two companies, the City and South London Railway and the Charing Cross, Euston and Hampstead Railway, in the 1890s and 1900s.",
        "interchange-keep-sitting is fare paying false" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_24> prov:value "Following the practice adopted during the transfer of former Silverlink services to London Overground in 2007, TfL carried out a deep clean of stations and trains on the future Elizabeth line route, installed new ticket machines and barriers, introduced Oyster card and contactless payment, and ensured all stations were staffed.",
        "High Street Kensington station in 1892 In 1863, the Metropolitan Railway, the world's first underground railway, opened in London between Paddington and Farringdon, connecting the Great Western Railway's relatively remote terminus at Paddington with Euston and King's Cross stations and the Paddington, London's financial district.",
        "List of boroughs in each zone: Zone Inner London Outer London Outside London 1 Central London: City of London, Camden, Hackney, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster 2 Camden, Hackney, Hammersmith & Fulham, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster Brent, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow 3 Camden, Hackney, Haringey, Islington, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Wandsworth Barnet, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow, Merton, Richmond upon Thames, Waltham Forest 4 Lewisham, Haringey, Newham Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Greenwich, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Merton, Redbridge, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex) 5 Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Harrow, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey) 6 Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Enfield, Harrow, Havering, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames Elmbridge (Surrey), Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey), Hertsmere (Hertfordshire), Reigate and Banstead (Surrey), Tandridge (Surrey), Three Rivers (Hertfordshire) Ancillary zones Further information: List of stations in London fare zones 7–14 For some services outside Greater London where fares are set by Transport for London, there are three additional zones 7, 8 and 9.",
        "The Railway came under the same ownership in 1913, and were physically connected and operationally merged in the 1920s, while at the same time extensions to Edgware and Morden were completed.",
        "This creates the situation where two consecutive stations on a radial route are in both zones - West Ham and Bromley by Bow; Stratford and Pudding Mill Lane; Canning Town and East India.",
        "interchange-keep-sitting is scheduled service false" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_25> prov:value "A traveller travelling to or from a two-zone station can, in certain circumstances, 'save' a zone and perhaps therefore pay a cheaper fare.",
        "Existing rolling stock was rebranded with the TfL Rail identity.[25] TfL Rail and Elizabeth line services Stage Map Completion dates Notes Schedule Actual Delay 0 Map of the first phase of Crossrail 2015 May 2015[26] 31 May 2015[27] — Existing \"metro\" service between Liverpool Street (main line station) and Shenfield transferred from Abellio Greater Anglia to TfL Rail 1 Map of the first phase of Crossrail 2015 May 2017[26] 22 June 2017[28] 1 month Class 345 trains start running between Liverpool Street and Shenfield in reduced length format[29] 2a[30] Map of the 2nd phase of Crossrail in 2018 May 2018[26] 20 May 2018[31] — Existing service between Paddington (main line station) and Heathrow Terminal 4 transferred from Heathrow Connect Existing shuttle service between Heathrow Terminals 2 & 3 and Heathrow Terminal 4 transferred from Heathrow Express, both to TfL Rail 5a[32] Map of Crossrail with Reading section —Paddington/a 15 December 2019[33] — Most stopping services between Paddington and Reading transferred from Great Western Railway to TfL Rail, operating up to 4 tph The first TfL trains in public service to Reading ran on 25 November 2019 as a soft launch of the service.[34] 2b[30] Map of the 2nd phase of Crossrail in 2018 May 2018[26] 30 July 2020[35] 2 years and 2 months Class 345 trains start running between Paddington and Heathrow 4a[36] Map of the first phase of Crossrail 2015 —Paddington/a 26 May 2021[37] — Class 345 trains in full length format start running between Liverpool Street and Shenfield[37] 3 Map of the 3rd phase of Crossrail 2018 Dec 2018[26] 24 May 2022[38] 3 years and 5 months Services between Paddington and Abbey Wood begin; this section and existing TfL Rail routes rebranded as the Elizabeth line, up to 12 tph 4b/5b Map of the 5th phase of Crossrail 2019 —N/a 6 November 2022[39] — Services begin between Paddington and Shenfield; and between Reading and Abbey Wood; and between Heathrow and Abbey Wood.",
        "In the 1930s and 1940s the Northern line took over and electrified the London and North Eastern Railway branches to Mill Hill East and High Barnet.",
        "In the same year, a select committee report recommended an \"inner circle\" of railway lines connecting the London termini that had been built or were under construction.",
        "List of boroughs in each zone: Zone Inner London Outer London Outside London 1 Central London: City of London, Camden, Hackney, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster 2 Camden, Hackney, Hammersmith & Fulham, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster Brent, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow 3 Camden, Hackney, Haringey, Islington, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Wandsworth Barnet, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow, Merton, Richmond upon Thames, Waltham Forest 4 Lewisham, Haringey, Newham Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Greenwich, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Merton, Redbridge, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex) 5 Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Harrow, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey) 6 Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Enfield, Harrow, Havering, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames Elmbridge (Surrey), Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey), Hertsmere (Hertfordshire), Reigate and Banstead (Surrey), Tandridge (Surrey), Three Rivers (Hertfordshire) Ancillary zones Further information: List of stations in London fare zones 7–14 For some services outside Greater London where fares are set by Transport for London, there are three additional zones 7, 8 and 9.",
        "interchange-secure is tfl service false" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_26> prov:value "For example, travelling to West Ham from any zone 2 station is a single zone journey, but so is travelling there from any zone 3 station.",
        "In the next year, the Metropolitan District Railway (commonly known as the District Railway) was formed to build and operate a railway from South Kensington to Tower Hill.",
        "List of boroughs in each zone: Zone Inner London Outer London Outside London 1 Central London: City of London, Camden, Hackney, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster 2 Camden, Hackney, Hammersmith & Fulham, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster Brent, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow 3 Camden, Hackney, Haringey, Islington, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Wandsworth Barnet, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow, Merton, Richmond upon Thames, Waltham Forest 4 Lewisham, Haringey, Newham Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Greenwich, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Merton, Redbridge, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex) 5 Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Harrow, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey) 6 Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Enfield, Harrow, Havering, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames Elmbridge (Surrey), Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey), Hertsmere (Hertfordshire), Reigate and Banstead (Surrey), Tandridge (Surrey), Three Rivers (Hertfordshire) Ancillary zones Further information: List of stations in London fare zones 7–14 For some services outside Greater London where fares are set by Transport for London, there are three additional zones 7, 8 and 9.",
        "The services are operated in parallel, sharing the central tunnel.",
        "This was the final extension of the line for eight decades, though between the 1930s and 1970s the Northern City Line was branded and operated as part of the Northern line despite being disconnected from the rest of the line.",
        "interchange-secure is fare paying false" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_27> prov:value "5c Map of the 5th phase of Crossrail 2019 Dec 2019[26] 21 May 2023 3 years and 5 months Full route opens, with services between Heathrow and both Abbey Wood and Shenfield; and between Reading and Abbey Wood.",
        "In the next year, the Metropolitan District Railway (commonly known as the District Railway) was formed to build and operate a railway from South Kensington to Tower Hill.",
        "List of boroughs in each zone: Zone Inner London Outer London Outside London 1 Central London: City of London, Camden, Hackney, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster 2 Camden, Hackney, Hammersmith & Fulham, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster Brent, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow 3 Camden, Hackney, Haringey, Islington, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Wandsworth Barnet, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow, Merton, Richmond upon Thames, Waltham Forest 4 Lewisham, Haringey, Newham Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Greenwich, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Merton, Redbridge, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex) 5 Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Harrow, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey) 6 Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Enfield, Harrow, Havering, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames Elmbridge (Surrey), Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey), Hertsmere (Hertfordshire), Reigate and Banstead (Surrey), Tandridge (Surrey), Three Rivers (Hertfordshire) Ancillary zones Further information: List of stations in London fare zones 7–14 For some services outside Greater London where fares are set by Transport for London, there are three additional zones 7, 8 and 9.",
        "The most recent extension, a second southern branch from Kennington to Battersea, opened on 20 September 2021.",
        "Ticket machines American transportation system company Cubic Transportation Systems, known in the UK as Westinghouse Cubic Ltd until April 1997, has manufactured all of London Underground's ticket machines since 1987.",
        "interchange-secure is scheduled service false" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_28> prov:value "In the central section, there are interchanges with London Underground, National Rail, and Docklands Light Railway lines.[40] The Elizabeth line in the London transport network Geographical map of London rail and tube Geographical map Schematic map of London rail and tube Schematic map (interactive) Routes of the Elizabeth line (in purple, from middle of left edge to right edge), shown with London Underground and the Docklands Light Railway connections Design and infrastructure Elizabeth line roundel on a sign for Seven Kings station Name and identity Crossrail is the name of the construction project and of the limited Crossrail, wholly owned by TfL, that was formed to carry out construction works.[25][41] The \"Elizabeth line\" is the name of the new service that is on signage throughout the stations.",
        "List of boroughs in each zone: Zone Inner London Outer London Outside London 1 Central London: City of London, Camden, Hackney, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster 2 Camden, Hackney, Hammersmith & Fulham, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster Brent, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow 3 Camden, Hackney, Haringey, Islington, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Wandsworth Barnet, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow, Merton, Richmond upon Thames, Waltham Forest 4 Lewisham, Haringey, Newham Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Greenwich, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Merton, Redbridge, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex) 5 Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Harrow, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey) 6 Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Enfield, Harrow, Havering, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames Elmbridge (Surrey), Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey), Hertsmere (Hertfordshire), Reigate and Banstead (Surrey), Tandridge (Surrey), Three Rivers (Hertfordshire) Ancillary zones Further information: List of stations in London fare zones 7–14 For some services outside Greater London where fares are set by Transport for London, there are three additional zones 7, 8 and 9.",
        "The Metropolitan western extension from a new station at Paddington to South Kensington opened in 1868.",
        "There are proposals to split the line into two lines.",
        "Tickets are sold from various types of self-service machines; London Underground progressively closed all Underground station ticket offices in 2015-16.",
        "national-rail is tfl service false" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_29> prov:value "By May 1870, the District Railway had opened Railway line from West Brompton to Blackfriars via Gloucester Road and South Kensington, services being operated at first by the Metropolitan.[3] In 1871, the District had built a terminus at Mansion House, and on 18 November 1876 the Metropolitan opened Metropolitan terminus at Aldgate.[4] Because of the conflict between the two Metropolitan.[3, Metropolitan took an act of Parliament, the Metropolitan and District Railways (City Lines and Extensions) Act 1879 (42 & 43 Vict.",
        "In the central section, there are interchanges with London Underground, National Rail, and Docklands Light Railway lines.[40] The Elizabeth line in the London transport network Geographical map of London rail and tube Geographical map Schematic map of London rail and tube Schematic map (interactive) Routes of the Elizabeth line (in purple, from middle of left edge to right edge), shown with London Underground and the Docklands Light Railway connections Design and infrastructure Elizabeth line roundel on a sign for Seven Kings station Name and identity Crossrail is the name of the construction project and of the limited Crossrail, wholly owned by TfL, that was formed to carry out construction works.[25][41] The \"Elizabeth line\" is the name of the new service that is on signage throughout the stations.",
        "List of boroughs in each zone: Zone Inner London Outer London Outside London 1 Central London: City of London, Camden, Hackney, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster 2 Camden, Hackney, Hammersmith & Fulham, Islington, Kensington & Chelsea, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Tower Hamlets, Wandsworth and Westminster Brent, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow 3 Camden, Hackney, Haringey, Islington, Lambeth, Lewisham, Newham, Southwark, Wandsworth Barnet, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Greenwich, Hounslow, Merton, Richmond upon Thames, Waltham Forest 4 Lewisham, Haringey, Newham Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Brent, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Greenwich, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Merton, Redbridge, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex) 5 Barking and Dagenham, Barnet, Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Ealing, Enfield, Harrow, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, Waltham Forest Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey) 6 Bexley, Bromley, Croydon, Enfield, Harrow, Havering, Hillingdon, Hounslow, Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames Elmbridge (Surrey), Epping Forest (Essex), Epsom and Ewell (Surrey), Hertsmere (Hertfordshire), Reigate and Banstead (Surrey), Tandridge (Surrey), Three Rivers (Hertfordshire) Ancillary zones Further information: List of stations in London fare zones 7–14 For some services outside Greater London where fares are set by Transport for London, there are three additional zones 7, 8 and 9.",
        "The name for the system as installed from 1987 is \"UTS\" (Underground Ticketing System), though this system has been enhanced and extended recently, most notably since 1998 under the Prestige initiative, where Oyster smartcards were introduced.",
        "There are proposals to split the line into two lines.",
        "national-rail is fare paying true" .

<http://example.org/pt#stmt_3> prov:value "1 modified 2026-03-31T11:01:31.293Z",
        "Elizabeth line An Elizabeth line Class 345 train at Reading in January 2026 Overview System National Rail Locale Greater London Berkshire Buckinghamshire Essex Predecessor TfL Rail First service 24 May 2022; 3 years ago Current operator GTS Rail Operations (under concession from TfL)[1] Annual ridership 243 million Increase10% (2024/2025)[2] passenger journeys Website tfl.gov.uk/modes/elizabeth-line/ Edit this at Wikidata Route Termini West: Heathrow Terminal 4, Heathrow Terminal 5 and Reading East: Abbey Wood and Shenfield Stops 41 Distance travelled 117 km (73 mi)[3] Technical Rolling stock Class 345[4] Track gauge 1,435 mm (4 ft 8+1⁄2 in) standard gauge Electrification Overhead line, 25 kV 50 Hz AC Operating speed Core section: 95 km/h (60 mph) GWML, Heathrow and GEML: 145 km/h (90 mph) Track owners Transport for London (Old Oak Common–Abbey Wood and Stratford) Network Rail (Pudding Mill Lane–Shenfield, and Old Oak Common–Reading) Heathrow Airport Holdings (Heathrow branch) Transport for London rail lines The Elizabeth line is a railway line that runs across Greater London and nearby towns.",
        "Find sources: \"London Underground ticketing\" – news · newspapers · books · scholar · JSTOR (July 2009) (Learn how and when to remove this message) The London Underground and Docklands Light Railway (DLR) metro systems of London, England uses a mix of paper and electronic smart-card ticketing.",
        "Northern line 1995 Stock arrives at Stockwell tube station heading northbound to Edgware via Bank, July 2024 Overview Termini Kennington, Battersea Power Station, Morden Edgware, High Barnet, Mill Hill East Stations 52 Colour on map Black Website tfl.gov.uk/tube/route/northern/ Edit this at Wikidata Service Type Rapid transit System London Underground Depot(s) Golders GreenMorden Stabling Sidings: HighgateEdgwareHigh Barnet[1] Rolling stock 1995 Stock Ridership 339.7 million passenger journeys (2019)[2] History Opened 18 December 1890; 135 years ago (as City and South London Railway) 22 June 1907; 118 years ago (as Charing Cross, Euston & Hampstead Railway) 13 September 1926; 99 years ago (Lines merged) 28 August 1937; 88 years ago (Renamed to Northern line) Last extension 20 September 2021; 4 years ago Technical Line length 58 km (36 mi) Character Deep-tube Track gauge 1,435 mm (4 ft 8+1⁄2 in) standard gauge Electrification Fourth rail, 630 V DC Operating speed 45 mph (72 km/h)[3] Signalling CBTC (SelTrac) Transport for London rail lines The Northern line is a London Underground line that runs between North London and South London.",
        "Rail service fares in Greater London and the surrounding area are calculated in accordance with the London fare zones system managed by Transport for London.",
        "The railway is below ground in the central section and on the loop east of Paddington.",
        "bus is scheduled service true" .

